🥚🐟 TUNA EGG SALAD MEAL PREP 🐟🥚 listen… if you like chicken salad and tuna salad, that kind of thing, you’re gonna love this one too, I promise. Sounds interesting I know, but the flavors work!! 💁🏻‍♀️ Crunch from the veggies, protein from the eggs and tuna, brightness from the lemon juice, tons of flavor from the mustard and spices. It’ll surprise you!!
I like to enjoy it on bread or with some crackers and fruit for meal prep. ‼️BOOKMARK / SAVE this one for later!!📌

Here are the ingredients! 
1 (5 ounce) can of tuna, drained
4 large hard boiled eggs, roughly chopped
2 ribs celery, diced
2 medium dill pickles, diced
1/4 small red onion, diced
1/2 cup mayonnaise
1 tablespoon lemon juice
2 teaspoons dijon mustard
1/2 teaspoon garlic powder
1/2 teaspoon salt
1/4 teaspoon fresh ground black pepper

🌿💵 VEGGIES VS DOLLARS Part 1!!💵🌿 okay, I was hesitant to get this going cause it’s not my normal thing but I’m passionate about plants and growing vegetables at home, so maybe this’ll help you get to know me while following along with a food and garden experiment at the same time!! 👩🏻‍🌾
🌿 WHAT I’M DOING: this growing season, I’m doing an experiment to see if I can grow more veggies in my yard than it actually costs to grow those veggies. Everything I harvest will be weighed and compared to the store price for organic produce of the same weight. I’ll be keeping track of all gardening costs as well.
🌿 DETAILS: to keep it simple, I’m only comparing the $ from if I grew veggies THIS YEAR compared to if I did not. I won’t be factoring in the cost of installing the beds or any work done in prior years (except the garlic I planted in the Fall). 
🌿 MY ZONE & CLIMATE: I live in Seattle, WA and I’m in zone 8b. My yard comes with gardening challenges such as lots of trees along the west of the property which blocks all late afternoon sun to most of my garden space. I’m also in a bit of a valley with a creek and hills on both sides, which creates a sort of microclimate with less sun and extra moisture than places even 1/2 mile away. Any veggies that require full sun (12+ hours) just don’t work.
🌿 MY GARDEN SPACE: I’ve got 2 in ground beds that were here when I moved in, honestly not the most well placed but they work. Last year I installed a tall @vego_garden bed that I’m obsessed with! I also use buckets for tomatoes and I have 2 young blueberry bushes that got me like 12 berries total last year.
🌿 WHAT WORKS: In the past, herbs did really well in my front raised bed. The back pair of beds have housed garlic for a couple years now. Quick growing veggies like carrots and radish have done well, and I’m always growing multiple kinds of lettuce and spinach. That’s my main crop! 
🌿 MY PLAN: Grow, harvest and enjoy as much as I can while actually paying attention to how much I’m bringing in!
👩🏻‍🌾🌿💵 FOLLOW ALONG ALL GROWING SEASON TO SEE HOW I DO 😊✨ 1st cost update coming in Part 2!

🌿💵 VEGGIES VS DOLLARS Part 2!!💵🌿 you’re probably not surprised to learn this is the spending $ part of the season!! This is my first cost breakdown of the veggies vs dollars series, covering everything I’ve purchased for this growing season from garlic last fall to seeds last week!! Here’s a complete list of everything I talked about in the Reel with a little more info:
🌿 GARLIC STARTS: last October I bought four heads of garlic at the nursery - two hardneck varieties: Killarney red and Korean hardneck. I planted them in the Fall and they should be ready to harvest around July. This cost 💲17
🌿 SEEDS: I got romaine, basil mix, Thai basil, cilantro, radishes, spinach, and bunching green onion seeds. This cost 💲16
🌿 HARDWARE CLOTH: if you’ve been following my battle with squirrels then you know why I need this. This cost 💲16
🌿 SOIL: I got 4 bags of organic soil from Costco which included compost. This cost 💲34.76
🌿 MULCH CUBE: Mulch helps with water retention and suppressing weeds. Plus adds more organic plant matter that eventually works it’s way into the soil. This cost 💲24
🌿 WHEELBARROW: My neighbor gave me this for free!
🌿 FERTILIZER: I had some leftover from last year so I’m using that before I buy any more.
➡️➡️ total costs so far: $107.76

👩🏻‍🌾 HARVEST:
🌿 parsley - I harvested one big bunch of parsley worth $1.99
➡️➡️ total grown so far: $1.99

✨ For a difference of: -$105.77 🫣

☀️ follow along all season to see if I can grow all my money back!!! I’ll be planting seeds this weekend. Planning to do a cost update once a month at minimum over this year until things are done growing 💫

🍞🥑🍳 Saturday toast HASHBROWN edition & I’m starting toast talk 🎙️ lots of new people here thanks to my gardening series so I decided we could chat if you want 😅 here are my TOAST TALK TEN TIDBITS for today 🙋🏻‍♀️
1️⃣ hi, I’m Danielle. I’ve been posting toasts and breakfast sandwiches occasionally for a while now, but I want there to be a bit more meaning to these posts. So I’m turning it into TOAST TALK. 
2️⃣ I run a food blog website called Project Meal Plan where I share meal prep and make-ahead recipes. This is my full-time job since I started PMP in 2016. I often share pics and videos of my recipes, all found at ProjectMealPlan.com 🥪
3️⃣ Before this, I worked as a vocational rehabilitation counselor for 4 years. And before that, I worked at a student dining center in college. And first, before all of that, I worked at Jack in the Box in high school!
4️⃣ I am passionate about the environment and sustainability. I have a Bachelor’s degree in Environmental Science from Washington State University. Go Cougs!!
5️⃣ I’m a volunteer Seattle Urban Nature Guide (SUN guide!). This is how I step out of my comfort zone to help engage the community with nature in local parks and neighborhoods throughout Seattle. Since I work from home, this is my favorite way to get out of the house, meet people and get into nature.
6️⃣ The stickers on produce are not compostable. Peel them off and throw them away, don’t throw them in the compost. Is someone working on compostable food stickers?? I hope so.
7️⃣ I love breakfast. 
8️⃣ Over the last year or so, I’ve been struggling hard with endometriosis and adenomyosis (this one I had never heard of before the doctor told me). I’ll be having surgery for this on June 8th.
9️⃣ At 17, I took 900 pictures over a week in Europe. At 21, I made my roommates a video to celebrate our college graduation. So when I think about it, my career of photography and creating videos makes a lot of sense. 
🔟 Recently, I’m into birding. I’m getting better at identifying PNW birds! It’s my favorite, totally accessible to me hobby. 

Okay enough about me. If any of these things resonated with you, let’s chat!! Hi! 👋

🌿💵 VEGGIES VS DOLLARS Part 3️⃣!! 💵🌿 follow along as I try to GROW more in veggies than it COSTS to grow them!! 👩🏻‍🌾 today I’m giving an update on everything I planted and how it’s doing after about 3 weeks. Check out part 1 for all the info about this experiment and my garden setup, then check out part 2 for how I spent over $100 so far 😅 
💵 COSTS since part 2: 💵
🥕 4 tomato plants + some flowers: $22.97
🥕 sunflower sprout from a plant sale: $1
🥕 another bag of soil: $8.69
TOTAL SPENT THIS SEASON ➡️ $140.42

🌿 HARVESTS since part 2: 🌿
Nothing 😭
TOTAL HARVESTED THIS SEASON ➡️ $1.99

NEED TO GROW ➡️ $138.43 in veggies to break even!

Let’s just say I’ve got some growing to do!!

Some notes 🗒️ 
🥬 I planted the garlic last fall and it should be making scapes anytime! And then ready for harvest in July or so. 
🥬 I start most things from seeds directly sown except tomatoes - I don’t have a greenhouse or garage or shed to start these early, so I do buy starts and plant them around Mother’s Day. 
🥬 I know I could buy soil in bulk and it would be cheaper, but I don’t need that much and I don’t have anywhere to put it right now. 
🥬 I’ve never had such a bad problem with squirrels until this year. I’m trying to overseed some things like radish, and I really need to get more carrots, romaine and spinach out there.
🥬 my neighbor is basically a legit farmer and carpenter and he likes to yell over the fence, “do you have a _______??” And I say no and he brings over some plants. So far this year he has brought a huge artichoke plant and some mint (I put in a container don’t worry).
🥬 Gardening is definitely therapeutic for me and I certainly know there are benefits I can’t quantify. I’m just really curious about how much I’m actually growing! 
🥬 for simplicity, I’m only calculating this year’s costs!

There’s yours part 3 recap!! Hopefully by part 4 I’ll have some harvests to show you 😅

🌿 MY GOAL: Grow, harvest and enjoy as much as I can while actually paying attention to how much I’m bringing in!

🥬🐿️ DIY CONTAINER PROTECTION FOR SEEDLINGS 👩🏻‍🌾🐿️🥬 every single day I’m outside fixing something the squirrels dug up. It’s not a fun chore. BUT I finally found a way to protect seedlings and give them a head start. Here it is ⬆️⬆️⬆️ this worked successfully for my leafy lettuce as you can see! Not touched by squirrels a single time. WIN.

👩🏻‍🌾 of course there are limitations - avoid doing this with root veggies or things that don’t transplant well. Lettuce and chives are good ones to try!!
👩🏻‍🌾 leave about 2 inches of space between top of the soil and top rim of the pot so the seedlings have some space to grow before touching the netting.

🌿 let me know if you’re gonna try this!! I was honestly pretty proud of myself for thinking of this one 😅

🍌🍪 AIR FRYER COOKIE FOR ONE 🍪🍌 my newest air fryer creation, a delicious and chewy banana oatmeal cookie that only takes 8️⃣ minutes to cook in the air fryer!! ➡️ Here are the ingredients: ✨
1/2 ripe banana
1 1/2 tablespoons brown sugar, packed
1 tablespoon olive oil
1/4 teaspoon vanilla extract
1/4 cup rolled oats
3 tablespoons all-purpose flour
1/4 teaspoon cinnamon
1/4 teaspoon baking powder
1/8 teaspoon fine sea salt
1 tablespoon chocolate chips (plus more for topping if desired)

🍪 mix everything together in a little bowl, cut out some parchment paper (about 6x6 inches), line the basket, scoop the dough on to the parchment and flatten it out, then air fry at 320F for 8 minutes.

🌯🌶️ MEAL PREP SOY CHORIZO BREAKFAST BURRITOS 🌯 🌶️ are new on ProjectMealPlan.com! 🆕 if you love the taste of chorizo but you don’t love how greasy it gets, it’s time to try soy chorizo, aka Soyrizo!! 🍳🍴🫑 MEAL PREP BREAKFAST IDEA 🫑🍴🍳 quinoa egg protein bowls recipe from @plannedthenprepped 😍 I just prepped one of these glorious bowls for my breakfast today and one for tomorrow! I’m loving how simple to make and customizable they are. Make as many as you need!!
📌 SAVE this post for later so you remember this awesome breakfast idea!! Here’s the recipe:
🫑INGREDIENTS🫑 - makes 1 bowl (I doubled it for 2 bowls):
1/4 cup prepared quinoa
2 cherry tomatoes, sliced
1/8 red onion, chopped
1/8 bell pepper, chopped
1/4 cup spinach, chiffonade cut
1/4 cup 2 slices of ham, chopped
1 TB shredded cheese
1-2 eggs per bowl
Salt and pepper to taste
Hot sauce if you want!!

Add prepared quinoa, cut veggies, game and cheese to oven safe bowl. Put the lid on and store in the fridge if prepping ahead of time.
When you’re ready to cook, whisk 1-2 eggs into the bowl and add salt and pepper to taste. Add a little more cheese on top if you want 🧀
Bake at 425F for 10-15 minutes - mine was perfect at 10 minutes but it will depend on the thickness of your eggs in the bowl. 👩🏻‍🍳👩🏻‍🍳👩🏻‍🍳

🌿🌸4 garden fails of 2023🌸🌿 I’m still harvesting lettuce, carrots and tomatoes but since most of the growing season is over, I thought I’d share my 4 big fails of the year!! Always learning over here 👩🏻‍🌾

1️⃣ planted some seeds too early and they all sprouted and died when the temp dipped. Even better these were seeds I had collected from flowers the year before and I so smartly planted ALL of them 🙄
2️⃣ bunnies bunnies bunnies 🐰 They prefer the spinach and carrot tops. I could have done more. But they were a menace. Lost lots of produce to them!
3️⃣ sugar snap peas were terrible, super tough exterior and I didn’t even have the motivation to shell them for the peas inside 🫛 Didn’t get many overall. It could have been a result of the next one…
4️⃣ I learned the hard way that sunflowers 🌻 are allelopathic (I did say it wrong in the video, my bad), which means they emit a chemical that suppresses/kills other plants. Everything around the sunflower in half the herb garden bed was affected. Either killed or grew so poorly it wasn’t even worth it. Hopefully I can fix the soil for next year 😢

Those are my top gardening fails of the year!! What were yours? Happy Fall everyone! 🍂🍁

🌿💵 VEGGIES VS DOLLARS PART 5!! 💵🌿 experiment is over and results are in!! Quick recap ➡️ this growing season I did an experiment to see if I could grow more in veggies (estimated store price) than the cost of supplies to grow those veggies 🥕🥒🧄 You can find tons more info about my garden setup, costs, and progress in Parts 1-4!! 
💻 To keep track of harvests, I weighed everything and recorded it in a spreadsheet. Here’s what I grew in 2023 and how much it was worth in estimated store prices:
🥬 Lettuce & spinach: $72.70
💓 Radishes: $8.00
🫛 Snap Peas: $0.72
🧅 Green onions: $4.00
🌱 Garlic scapes: $5.00
🧄 Garlic: $32.16
🌿 Herbs (dill parsley basil mint & cilantro): $45.22
🥕 Carrots: $11.83 
🍅 Tomatoes: $29.62
🌾 Seeds: $4.18
🟰Total grown: $213.43
Costs: $152.40
Total grown - costs = money “grown”

‼️Some quick math shows I did grow more than I spent to grow it, and “made” $61.03‼️

👩🏻‍🌾 WOULD I DO THIS EXPERIMENT AGAIN?
I’m glad I did this experiment but would I do it again? No way. Here’s why: 
1. I got what I needed from this experiment! Now that I’ve satisfied my curiosity to know how much “money” I’m growing, I don’t need to do it again.
2. it prevented me from eating directly from the garden. Knowing I had to weigh it first to count kept me from garden snacking… which is one of the joys of gardening!
But I’m glad I did it! I learned a lot, such as
1. Yes, it’s possible to save money by growing your own food at home. 
2. What crops are saving me the most money by growing at home and where to focus my energy 
3. Garden spending patterns. High costs upfront and then you slowly make it all back.

Thanks for following along this Spring, Summer and Fall 🫶🏻

🌶️🍗 BUFFALO CHICKEN SALAD 🍗🌶️ simple, versatile, delicious and perfect for meal prep. It’s crunchy from the carrots and celery but creamy from the mayo and ranch combo 💁🏻‍♀️ keep this one in your back pocket as an alternative to the classic chicken salad 👖
📍📚 SAVE IT FOR LATER 💋🗂️
➡️ here’s the recipe because I love you: 😘 
1 pound leftover cooked, shredded chicken breasts (about 4 cups)
2 medium carrots, finely diced (about 1 cup)
2 stalks of celery, finely diced (about 1 1/4 cup)
1/4 red onion, finely diced
1/2 cup mayonnaise
1/3 cup Buffalo sauce (I use Frank’s Red Hot)
3 tablespoons Ranch dressing
1/2 teaspoon garlic powder
1/4 teaspoon each salt & fresh ground black pepper
✔️ mix it allllll together in a large bowl and that’s it! I like this chicken salad even more after it’s been in the fridge overnight. It’s delish by itself or you can serve it in a wrap/ on crackers/ however you want! ⭐️
